# Enhancement: Add graceful shutdown to CLI pipeline

## Context
Long-running ingestion pipelines (historical data ingestion spanning months) can take hours, especially for large active repositories. Currently, pressing Ctrl+C immediately terminates the process, losing all in-progress work.

This is common when:
- Ingesting historical data for the first time
- Running large date range imports (e.g., `--after 2024-01-01`)
- Processing multiple large repositories
- Debugging or testing ingestion locally

## Proposal
Add graceful shutdown handling that:
1. **First Ctrl+C**: Completes current operation, saves progress, then exits cleanly
2. **Second Ctrl+C**: Force exits immediately if user needs to stop now
3. Shows clear messaging about shutdown state
4. Allows resuming with same command (pipeline skips already-processed data)

## Implementation

### Add to `cli/analyze-pipeline.ts` (before program definition):

```typescript
// Graceful shutdown handler
let gracefulShutdown = false;
process.on("SIGINT", () => {
  if (!gracefulShutdown) {
    gracefulShutdown = true;
    (global.process as { gracefulShutdown?: boolean }).gracefulShutdown = true;
    console.log(
      "\n‚ö†Ô∏è  Graceful shutdown initiated... Current operations will complete.",
    );
    console.log("Press Ctrl+C again to force exit.");
  } else {
    console.log("\nüî¥ Force exit requested.");
    process.exit(1);
  }
});
```

### Update ingest command execution (in ingest action handler):

```typescript
try {
  await ingestPipeline(undefined, context);

  if (gracefulShutdown) {
    rootLogger.warn(
      "‚ö†Ô∏è  Ingestion interrupted but current operations completed successfully!",
    );
    rootLogger.info(
      "üí° You can resume by running the same command again - the pipeline will skip already processed data.",
    );
  } else {
    rootLogger.info("‚úÖ Ingestion completed successfully!");
  }
} catch (error: unknown) {
  if (String(error).includes("GRACEFUL_SHUTDOWN")) {
    rootLogger.warn(
      "‚ö†Ô∏è  Ingestion gracefully interrupted. Progress has been saved.",
    );
    rootLogger.info("üí° Resume by running the same command again.");
    return;
  }
  throw error;
}
```

### Update `src/lib/pipelines/types.ts` mapStep to respect shutdown:

```typescript
const results = await pMap(
  inputs,
  async (item, index) => {
    // Check for graceful shutdown before processing each item
    if (
      global.process &&
      (global.process as { gracefulShutdown?: boolean }).gracefulShutdown
    ) {
      context.logger?.warn(
        `Graceful shutdown requested. Skipping remaining items after ${index}/${inputs.length}`,
      );
      throw new Error("GRACEFUL_SHUTDOWN");
    }
    return await operation(item, context);
  },
  {
    concurrency: Math.max(1, concurrency),
    stopOnError: false, // Continue processing other items even if one fails
  },
);

return results.filter((r) => r !== null); // Filter out any null results from interrupted operations
```

## Benefits
- ‚úÖ Better UX for long-running operations (common in this project)
- ‚úÖ No lost work on interruption - current operation completes
- ‚úÖ Clear user feedback about shutdown state
- ‚úÖ Resume capability - just re-run the same command
- ‚úÖ Safety valve with double Ctrl+C for immediate exit

## Trade-offs
- Uses global state (`gracefulShutdown` flag on process object)
- Adds ~30-40 lines of code
- Slight complexity in pipeline execution flow

## User Experience

### Before (current behavior):
```bash
$ bun run pipeline ingest --after 2024-01-01
Fetching data for ethereum-optimism/optimism...
^C [Process killed immediately, no progress saved]
```

### After (with graceful shutdown):
```bash
$ bun run pipeline ingest --after 2024-01-01
Fetching data for ethereum-optimism/optimism...
^C
‚ö†Ô∏è  Graceful shutdown initiated... Current operations will complete.
Press Ctrl+C again to force exit.
‚ö†Ô∏è  Ingestion interrupted but current operations completed successfully!
üí° You can resume by running the same command again - the pipeline will skip already processed data.

$ bun run pipeline ingest --after 2024-01-01
[Resumes from where it left off]
```

